SIMPLE: entireness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Entireness
<hw>En*tire"ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
state or condition of being entire; completeness; fullness; totality;
<as>as, the <ex>entireness</ex> of an arch or a bridge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This same <qex>entireness</qex> or completeness.</q>
<rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Integrity; wholeness of heart; honesty.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Entireness</qex> in preaching the gospel.</q>
<rj><qau>Udall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Oneness; unity; -- applied to a condition of
intimacy or close association.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>True Christian love may be separated from acquaintance, and
acquaintance from <qex>entireness</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Entirety</ent>⟦br⟧
